      • A Leg Even at Yale - An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, AACC Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Our objective is to raise awareness and strengthen peer support systems for all first-generation and/or low-income students at Yale. As a registered student organization on campus, A.L.E. will be open to all interested participants, regardless of their financial background. We intend to work alongside other student groups, dedicated faculty, and members of the administration to benefit the largest number of students possible.

      • AFROTC Undergraduate Association

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Pre-Professional

        Website Mission

        Mission
        We are committed to ensuring that all members have every opportunity to develop as young officers (for those who are AFROTC cadets), and as Yale students, mentally, morally, and physically. Often, the cost of required AFROTC events and training evolutions cannot be covered by official AFROTC unit funds, meaning that the cost is passed down to the cadets. We want to ensure that no cadet is ever limited in their training as future officers, and therefore we will strive to provide them with the resources they need. As an organization, the three main resources we provide are (1) an inclusive community for all members, (2) financial assistance for ROTC training activities, and (3) events that connect Association members with the U.S. Air Force, Yale AFROTC alumni, and the many resources provided by Yale University.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission

      • AIDS Walk New Haven

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        We seek to raise money for the major AIDS service organizations, including AIDS Project New Haven, Fair Haven Community Health Center, Cornell Scott Hill Health Center, Leeway, Liberty Community Services, New Reach, Planned Parenthood, and Yale Child Study Center. Because we are an all-volunteer organization, we are able to commit the maximum possible amount of funds raised to the fight against HIV/AIDS in New Haven. We seek to Increase public awareness and promote prevention through advocacy by uniting as a community to speak out about the need for greater HIV/AIDS prevention and treatment resources. Every business, school, and individual that participates in and contributes to the AIDS Walk will be actively helping more children and adults understand the importance of HIV education, prevention and treatment in the greater New Haven area. We seek to unite the Yale and New Haven community against stigma, apathy and infection. AIDS blurs borders, crosses class lines and unites races in suffering. It truly is everyone's problem, and so we invite you to be a part of the solution.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        We seek to raise money for the major AIDS service organizations, including AIDS Project New Haven, Fair Haven Community Health Center, Cornell Scott Hill Health Center, Leeway, Liberty Community Services, New Reach, Planned Parenthood, and Yale Child Study Center.       • AIESEC

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, Entrepreneurial/Business, International Affairs, Leadership, Service/Volunteering, Social

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        AIESEC Yale is a student-run non-profit organization. Our main mission is to improve cultural understanding by facilitating international exchanges based around the UN Sustainable Development Goals. In the past, we have sent Yalies to Italy to help refugees, China and Argentina to teach English, and Peru to support a monkey sanctuary. We have also hosted international volunteers from India, Kuwait, Peru, and Egypt to work with local New Haven NGOs including CT Fund for the Environment, MakeHaven, and Common Ground.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission

Our main mission is to improve cultural understanding by facilitating international exchanges based around the UN Sustainable Development Goals. In the past, we have sent Yalies to Italy to help refugees, China and Argentina to teach English, and Peru to support a monkey sanctuary. We have also hosted international volunteers from India, Kuwait, Peru, and Egypt to work with local New Haven NGOs including CT Fund for the Environment, MakeHaven, and Common Ground.

      • Alexander Hamilton Society: Yale Undergraduate Chapter

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - International Affairs

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Alexander Hamilton Society (AHS) is a non-partisan, not-for-profit, national organization that seeks to identify, educate, and launch young men and women into foreign policy and national security careers imbued with the Hamiltonian perspective of strong and principled American leadership in global affairs. Hamiltonians are united by a deep conviction, rooted in the history of the last century, that the world is a better, safer, and more prosperous place when the United States is willing and able to lead. Engaging citizens from all walks of life and at every stage in their careers, AHS seeds the ground for the future of American foreign policy.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Alexander Hamilton Society (AHS) is a non-partisan, not-for-profit, national organization that seeks to identify, educate, and launch young men and women into foreign policy and national security careers imbued with the Hamiltonian perspective of strong and principled American leadership in global affairs. Hamiltonians are united by a deep conviction, rooted in the history of the last century, that the world is a better, safer, and more prosperous place when the United States is willing and able to lead. Engaging citizens from all walks of life and at every stage in their careers, AHS seeds the ground for the future of American foreign policy.

      • Alliance for Dance at Yale College

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Dance

        Website Mission

        Mission
        As an umbrella organization we seek to unite the dance groups on campus, bring together the New Haven and Yale dance community and to work for more administrative support for dance on campus. We believe that there should be maximum cooperation within the campus dance community and that as the dance community grows it is important for us to work with the administration to accommodate their needs of rehearsal and performance space.



        The Alliance for Dance at Yale is an umbrella organization which seeks to unite the dance groups on campus, bring together the New Haven and Yale dance community and to work for more administrative support for dance on campus. We book rehearsal space at Payne Whitney Gym for all undergraduate dance groups, and we host the Festival of Dance Groups during Opening Days for freshman. The Alliance automatically includes all members of dance groups on campus and is led by a board of directors who are elected by the larger membership each year. This board consists of 5 positions all of which may be held by 1 or 2 people: executive director publicity director treasurer outreach coordinator secretary Additionally a representative from each dance group who wishes to participate in ADAY activities will serve as a direct liason to the board and help in the planning and production of ADAY events. As an umbrella organization we seek to unite the dance groups on campus, bring together the New Haven and Yale dance community and to work for more administrative support for dance on campus. We believe that there should be maximum cooperation within the campus dance community and that as the dance community grows it is important for us to work with the administration to accomodate their needs of rehearsal and performance space. There are no membership requirements, though people wishing to hold office within ADAY must be currently enrolled undergraduates. Elections are held yearly in January. Interested candidate submit a candidate statement to the Alliance and are elected by majority vote.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission

We believe that there should be maximum cooperation within the campus dance community and that as the dance community grows it is important for us to work with the administration to accommodate their needs of rehearsal and performance space.

      • Alliance for Southeast Asian Students

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, AACC Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Alliance for Southeast Asian Students was formed in order to promote, examine and discuss the culture, economies and socio-political developments of Southeast Asian countries and their people along with fostering a close community of Southeast Asian students and those interested in Southeast Asia at Yale University. Each year, we embrace new Southeast Asians and other interested students, both undergraduate and some graduate, to our organization and host events open to the Yale public that encourage interest in Southeast Asia, events that include but are not limited to roundtable discussions, speaker events, food events and film events. Our mission is not only to represent our respective countries in the student body to the best of our abilities, mainly through active discussion in academic and social events at the university, but to encourage a better understanding of Southeast Asia and aid in publicizing Southeast Asian related events on campus to those who of the Yale public who might be interested.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Alliance for Southeast Asian Students was formed in order to promote, examine and discuss the culture, economies and socio-political developments of Southeast Asian countries and their people along with fostering a close community of Southeast Asian students and those interested in Southeast Asia at Yale University. Each year, we embrace new Southeast Asians and other interested students, both undergraduate and some graduate, to our organization and host events open to the Yale public that encourage interest in Southeast Asia, events that include but are not limited to roundtable discussions, speaker events, food events and film events. Our mission is not only to represent our respective countries in the student body to the best of our abilities, mainly through active discussion in academic and social events at the university, but to encourage a better understanding of Southeast Asia and aid in publicizing Southeast Asian related events on campus to those who of the Yale public who might be interested.

      • Alzheimer's Buddies

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        NAB functions by pairing college students with residents in local Alzheimer’s/dementia care facilities for weekly one-on-one visits. These students work with both family members and staff to determine the best way to utilize their visits in order to learn more about the interests and lives of the residents, thereby forming connections that help combat the isolation often felt by residents in such facilities. Additionally, NAB chapters in the past have helped educate campus communities about AD, launched music therapy initiatives, and performed clinical research studies. For more information about NAB, please see www.alzbuddies.org.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        NAB functions by pairing college students with residents in local Alzheimer’s/dementia care facilities for weekly one-on-one visits. These students work with both family members and staff to determine the best way to utilize their visits in order to learn more about the interests and lives of the residents, thereby forming connections that help combat the isolation often felt by residents in such facilities. For more information about NAB, please see www.alzbuddies.org.

      • American Red Cross at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Ngozi Okoli

        Mission
        The American Red Cross at Yale seeks to serve as a local community service organization at Yale and in New Haven, providing aid on a more regional scale than its parent organization. We serve as an intermediary between the students and faculty of Yale University and the American Red Cross. We host blood drives on the Yale campus, recruiting Yale graduate and undergraduate students as well as the broader community to donate blood and fulfill the Red Cross's local blood needs.

        Membership Benefits

      • American Sign Language at Yale--An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic

        Website Mission

        Mission
        ASLaY seeks to foster a community of diverse ASL signers of all abilities and backgrounds. We aim to provide a space for those interested in sign language to gather and to learn from one another. In addition, we seek to celebrate the beauty and poeticism of sign. ASLaY seeks to fill a gap in the representation of languages on Yale's campus. We try to advocate for more ASL opportunities on campus to further foster and develop a campus-wide appreciation of ASL.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

      • Asian American Health Advocates

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, Health/Wellness, AACC Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Mission
        AAHA is made up of Yale undergraduates who are passionate about the humanistic side of medicine. With many of us as students pursuing careers in medicine, healthcare and public and global health, we recognize that our current healthcare system falls short in many ways. We want to analyze the ways in which various social determinants of health result in healthcare disparities, ultimately affecting the accessibility and quality of care for many minority groups.

        Membership Benefits

      • Ballet Folklórico Mexicano de Yale - Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Dance, La Casa Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Ballet Folklórico Mexicano de Yale was founded in the fall of 1998 by a group of undergraduate students dedicated to the expression of Mexican culture and traditional folk dance. Since its founding, the group has had the privilege of performing at numerous cultural and educational events at Yale, throughout Connecticut, and elsewhere in the Northeast. As the only Mexican folk dance group on campus, Ballet Folklórico does not hold auditions. Our goals are both diverse and ambitious: while providing an outlet for the exploration of our heritage, we seek to enrich students’ cultural knowledge, and serve as a resource for greater Connecticut communities as well.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Ballet Folklórico Mexicano de Yale was founded in the fall of 1998 by a group of undergraduate students dedicated to the expression of Mexican culture and traditional folk dance. Since its founding, the group has had the privilege of performing at numerous cultural and educational events at Yale, throughout Connecticut, and elsewhere in the Northeast. As the only Mexican folk dance group on campus, Ballet Folklórico does not hold auditions. Our goals are both diverse and ambitious: while providing an outlet for the exploration of our heritage, we seek to enrich students’ cultural knowledge, and serve as a resource for greater Connecticut communities as well.

      • Berkeley College Orchestra

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Instruments

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Berkeley College Orchestra is dedicated to the promotion of a musical presence on the Yale campus and the greater Connecticut area. To achieve this goal, the BCO provides a place for students to study and practice the performance of music without grades and seeks to foster a community of musicians with similar goals. To this end, BCO holds weekly rehearsals and three free public concerts during the school year and one educational concert for New Haven public school students.

      • Black Pre-Health Students at Yale - an Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Medical/Nursing/Public Health

        Website Mission

        Mission
        We are a student organization dedicated to inaugurating an empowering, educational, and preparatory environment for students across the African diaspora interested in pursuing a health-related profession. We incorporate the various branches of health and create an atmosphere that encourages critical conversation, community engagement, and a humanistic approach to medicine. Because of the historical oppression of Black populations in healthcare at large, we hope to increase the numbers of prepared Black leaders and healers in health advocacy and clinical settings.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        We are a student organization dedicated to inaugurating an empowering, educational, and preparatory environment for students across the African diaspora interested in pursuing a health-related profession. We incorporate the various branches of health and create an atmosphere that encourages critical conversation, community engagement, and a humanistic approach to medicine. Because of the historical oppression of Black populations in healthcare at large, we hope to increase the numbers of prepared Black leaders and healers in health advocacy and clinical settings.

      • Black Student Alliance at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Black Student Alliance at Yale (BSAY) is a multi-cultural organization dedicated to enhancing the lives of Black students at Yale through political action, community action, and social events. Understanding that the world changes for the better through the determined efforts of concerned people, and that we are strongest when we are united, BSAY exists in order to create that unity and foster that change in hopes of furthering the cause of equality. As a student-run organization, BSAY is responsible for advocating for the students at Yale, taking political stands, and creating the sense of community necessary to unite students to work for positive change. On campus, we strive to meet the needs of the Black community by holding weekly meetings that are pertinent to the lives of Black students on campus and that create a supportive community for all Black students at Yale. BSAY strives create a safe and active community in order to adequately represent and respond to the Black community. This sense of community must come from both current social activities and from a sense of shared history and culture. Our strength comes from not only the collective struggle of our contemporaries but also the cumulative struggles of thousands who have sacrificed before us. Let us strive in our efforts so that we may fulfill the dreams of those who struggled before and brighten the futures of those yet to come.

      • Bulldog Brewing

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Food/Culinary

        Website Mission

        Mission
        In College life, drinking is often tied up into partying. This obscures the rich history and creative experience behind some of the drinks we frequently enjoy. Bulldog Brewing would aim to make students reflect on their construction of alcohol, providing students with a space to invest their time, labor, and creativity. Throughout the semester, we would be coming together to create the initial batches of beer, bottle the beer after fermentation, and taste the beers after carbonation, taking attentive notes about the beer's notes, taste, color and more. Students will feel invested in the beer and see how alcoholic drinks are not merely just valued for their alcohol.

      • Cadence of Yale - Undergraduate A Cappella

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Singing

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        We are Cadence of Yale, Yale University’s newest a cappella group! At a school known for tradition, we aim to break the mold by being the first group dedicated to competition and active participation within the international a cappella community. We are also dedicated to using a cappella as a medium for storytelling, conveying emotion, and addressing mental health and sociopolitical issues. To borrow the words of Deke Sharon, we want to create “harmony through harmony” by making meaningful music for our audiences and ourselves. We mostly sing pop and alternative pop music (such as “The Ballad of Me and My Brain” by The 1975, “Darkness Keeps Chasing Me” by Grace VanderWaal, and “Reasons Not to Die” by Ryn Weaver), and we’re very excited to work with amazing arrangers like Matt Goldstein of the Vassar Devils while crafting our set! As a brand-new group, we can’t wait to cultivate our sound this year and show it to the world.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        We are Cadence of Yale, Yale University’s newest a cappella group! At a school known for tradition, we aim to break the mold by being the first group dedicated to competition and active participation within the international a cappella community. We are also dedicated to using a cappella as a medium for storytelling, conveying emotion, and addressing mental health and sociopolitical issues. To borrow the words of Deke Sharon, we want to create “harmony through harmony” by making meaningful music for our audiences and ourselves. We mostly sing pop and alternative pop music (such as “The Ballad of Me and My Brain” by The 1975, “Darkness Keeps Chasing Me” by Grace VanderWaal, and “Reasons Not to Die” by Ryn Weaver), and we’re very excited to work with amazing arrangers like Matt Goldstein of the Vassar Devils while crafting our set! As a brand-new group, we can’t wait to cultivate our sound this year and show it to the world.

      • Chi Alpha Christian Fellowship

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Religious/Spiritual

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        ARTICLE I - NAME

        The name of this organization shall be Chi Alpha Christian Fellowship (XA) at Yale University. This will be the special name and acronym used to refer to our group on and off campus and among other organizations.

        ARTICLE II - PURPOSE

        The purpose of Chi Alpha shall be to develop the spiritual life and abilities of the students in relation to God, to each other, and to the world at large within a Pentecostal Christian context and in a manner consistent with the teachings of the Assemblies of God USA. Chi Alpha is open to all Yale undergraduate students and, though its name is Greek, it is not a fraternity or sorority. The name is a reflection of the National Chi Alpha Christian campus organization. As part of this mission, Chi Alpha seeks to introduce fellow collegians to an authentic relationship with Jesus Christ. Chi Alpha plans to do this through:



        1. Prayer - Communication with God.

        2. Worship - Expressions of thanks through word, music, and service.

        3. Fellowship - Community of students developing quality relationships.

        4. Discipleship - Learning about Jesus and following His example.

        5. Mission - Living a life that reflects our relationship with God in what we say and do.

        Chi Alpha is a member of Yale Religious Ministries whose external Directors are Affiliated Chaplains of Yale University.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

      • China Hands Magazine

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Publication

        Website Mission

        Contact: Emily Lin, Email group officers

        Mission
        The US-China relationship is widely recognized as the most important bilateral relationship in the 21st century. The United States and China dominate the world in terms of economic output, military spending, and geopolitical influence. Leaders from both the US and China have endeavored to build a symbiotic relationship between the two countries. China Hands Magazine seeks to extend the project of strengthening US-China relations to students from both countries.

        We see a dearth of student publications dedicated to promoting US-China relations on campuses in the US or China. In order to fulfill this mutual intellectual curiosity of students from both countries, we have built a platform for discussion and education about China-related issues and US-China relations.

        Membership Benefits

      • Chinese American Students Association

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, AACC Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Chinese American Students Association is designed to facilitate a Chinese American community that educates the Yale University campus on anything and everything that involves Chinese Americans and Asian Americans today. CASA tries to further political activism for Chinese American and Asian American interests on campus, seeking to be not only reactive but also proactive in its search to further the Chinese American/Asian American political agenda. CASA is heavily involved with the Asian American Students Alliance / Political Action committee and works cooperatively with all the other organizations on campus in order to provide the optimal power and voice for the Chinese American community. In addition to nurturing political awareness concerning Chinese Americans, Chinese American Students Association also strives to promote social interaction and unity through numerous popular activities like hosting our annual Lunar New Year event, Cultural Show, mixers, and other social activities. CASA also plays a sizable role in organizing and driving many activities during Asian Pacific American month. Others include study breaks, karaoke nights and movie screenings. CASA also reaches beyond the Yale community by taking trips to New York's Chinatown, creating intercollegiate coalition with other CSAs such as Harvard's CSA and Columbia's CSC and inviting guest speakers to Yale. CASA also plays a role locally in New Haven, with a community outreach program seeks to encourage interaction between Yale and Chinese American children from the New Haven area.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Chinese American Students Association is designed to facilitate a Chinese American community that educates the Yale University campus on anything and everything that involves Chinese Americans and Asian Americans today. CASA tries to further political activism for Chinese American and Asian American interests on campus, seeking to be not only reactive but also proactive in its search to further the Chinese American/Asian American political agenda. CASA is heavily involved with the Asian American Students Alliance / Political Action committee and works cooperatively with all the other organizations on campus in order to provide the optimal power and voice for the Chinese American community.       • Chocolate And Confectionary Artisans Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Food/Culinary

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The purpose of CACAO is to advance interest in the fields of the culinary arts. Cultivation of appreciation of fine chocolate, a gourmet commodity, is learned skill and a key goal of the organization. Our members will develop a greater respect for chocolate as a food item that pervades communities and cultures across the world. A focus of CACAO is also to foster a deeper understanding of the larger implications of chocolate in the world: the history behind chocolate, the production of chocolate, the nutritional impact of chocolate, and the relevance of chocolate in culture. CACAO will highlight outreach and education; our goal to focus on sustainable methods will be accomplished by purchasing resources from suppliers with an understanding of fair advocacy in chocolate production and hosting events and activities that promote social awareness.

      • Club of Argentine Students at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural

        Website Mission

        Contact: Juan Recoaro, Email group officers

        Mission
        The Club of Argentine Students at Yale will first and foremost strive to advance Argentine culture within the Yale Community. The Club will provide an institutional framework to allow for regular gatherings of individuals from Argentina, and as those interested in its culture. Similarly, the Club will coordinate events including, but not limited to, guest speakers, Argentine art expositions, and film screenings. This cultural advocacy will provide a space for discussion and learning about Argentine culture amid the whole of the Yale community. Furthermore, the Club will provide orientation and support for incoming or prospective Argentine students to ensure their inclusion in the Yale community. Finally, the Club will establish institutional relationships with similar organizations in other Universities and other networks with similar purposes such as the Yale Alumni Club of Argentina.

      • Design for America at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Arts: Other

        Website Mission

        Contact: Sophie Lai, Linna Yao, Email group officers

        Mission
        Design for America (DFA) is an award-winning nationwide network of university students using design innovation for social good. We are part of the nationwide network that started at Northwestern University in 2009. DFA's mission is to provide students the opportunity to work on diverse interdisciplinary teams, where they learn to apply a human-centered design philosophy to solve real, complex problems alongside passionate community members. We encourage students to apply their vast skill-sets to create social impact in their local communities through design thinking. DFA desires to build a strong student community that allows each student the capacity to take on any challenge they encounter in the future.

      • Distilled Periodical

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Publication

        Website Mission

        Contact: Sherry Xu, Julianna Gross, Email group officers

        Mission
        I. Interdisciplinary Ethos: DISTILLED believes that innovations in science and technology give rise to ethical and political concerns that demand rigorous interdisciplinary discourse. Articles published in DISTILLED must be opinion pieces centered around a policy-relevant issue. An original claim or argument must be made, backed by primary academic literature sources. Furthermore, some kind of solution or follow-up action(s) should be proposed or explored.

        II. Inclusivity: Contributing writers, editors, and other DISTILLED team members need no previous journalism experience -- any student passionate about interdisciplinary science and its implications for social and public policy can, throughout our extensive editorial process, work with other students, postdocs, and professors to develop ideas into articles rigorously supported by primary scientific literature.
        DISTILLED strives to lower the barrier to entry of scientific publication and provide socially-oriented students of diverse backgrounds the resources and networks they need to develop their ideas into publishable essays.

        III. Mentorship: As a campus-wide organization whose editorial team, authors, and readership unite undergraduate, graduate, and professional students from diverse scientific disciplines across Yale, DISTILLED has a unique opportunity to foster formal and informal communities of mentorship. Particularly, working on the publication and attending DISTILLED meetings and events affords undergraduate students the opportunity to meet more experienced student scientists and researchers, learn from their trajectories, and build mentoring relationships. More generally, by bringing together diverse students in shared work and space, DISTILLED is a hub for organic cross-disciplinary, cross-cohort community and collaboration.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Sherry Xu, Julianna Gross, Email group officers

        Mission
        I. Interdisciplinary Ethos: DISTILLED believes that innovations in science and technology give rise to ethical and political concerns that demand rigorous interdisciplinary discourse. Articles published in DISTILLED must be opinion pieces centered around a policy-relevant issue. An original claim or argument must be made, backed by primary academic literature sources. Furthermore, some kind of solution or follow-up action(s) should be proposed or explored.

        II.       • DOWN Magazine

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, LGBTQ, Publication, AACC Affiliate Org, AfAm Affiliate Org, NACC Affiliate Org, Cultural: Mixed Race

        Website Mission

        Contact: Jennifer Qu, Email group officers

        Mission
        The purpose of this organization is to amplify the diverse voices and interests of students of color at Yale, and to provide a safe space for those students to be their full selves. DOWN was born because of a dearth of excellent journalism covering the topics that matter to students of color at Yale. Our goal is primarily to provide that coverage. Our secondary goal is to provide a supportive space for students of color to challenge each other to become better writers, and to encourage and train new writers to help them find their voice. We achieve this goal through frequent writing workshops led by people like Mark Oppenheimer, Director of the Yale Journalism Initiative and various faculty members of the English Department at Yale.

        Membership Benefits

      • Elm City Echo

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Arts: Other, Publication, Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Chibuzo Enelamah, Eliana Swerdlow, Email group officers

        Mission
        The Elm City Echo aims to promote awareness of homelessness and displacement by giving contributors a community-oriented platform to amplify their voices and experiences. The Echo empowers individuals through the process of sharing while centralizing creators’ voices. Since 2011, student volunteers have worked with individuals experiencing extreme poverty and homelessness to record and publish the prose, poetry, and artwork. Each collaboration begins with volunteers visiting one of our community partners (Columbus House or Fellowship Place) to facilitate the storytelling process. Once a semester, we publish the pieces in a literary magazine that is freely distributed around New Haven.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Chibuzo Enelamah, Eliana Swerdlow, Email group officers

        Mission
        The members of Engender fundamentally believe that our university's—and our country's—greatest strength is its abundant diversity. The vast array of experiences and talents possessed by Yale's student body is a central element of Yale's effect on its students through its curriculum and on the world through its research. While committed to celebrating success stories of inclusion at Yale and elsewhere, Engender also hopes to identify and work to overcome the remaining barriers to equal access and inclusion for women, students of color, and LGBTQ students at Yale and across the country. As Yale and some other educational institutions take increasingly strong stances in favor of equal opportunity in official university contexts, Engender hopes to complement these efforts by cultivating inclusive social spaces on and off campus to integrate all students into the fabric of the Yale community.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

      • European Horizons

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Yale Chapter will hold weekly meetings with members chosen from the Yale student body. These meetings will include think tank activities such as discussing possible policies that European governments or the European Union could implement in response to current events and crises. We will provide students with a platform to publish work pertaining to the European Union and European politics. The Yale Chapter will be responsible for organizing the European Horizons regional conference at Yale this year. This organization will hold speaker events open to the public, and will endeavor to include other like-minded organizations to bring the experts in the European field together. Through these series of activities we aim to have real impact on the state of the European Union and produce material that will be published in the European Horizons Journal, and other publications.

      • Every Vote Counts

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Advocacy/Policy

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The objective of Every Vote Counts at its core is rooted to this two-fold mission: more people should vote and the active voting population should reflect our nation’s demographics. To this end, our organizational divisions and offerings are tripartite. In our legislative policy and advocacy division, we oppose advances of gerrymandering and support pro-voter legislation that enhances fair districting. Next, through voter registration, social campaigns, and distribution of best practices, we hope to leverage technology along with comprehensive analysis of the practices of high turn-out nations in order to bolster robust voter engagement. Finally, we advocate at the local level in our Civic Education division through outreach to local high schools in our community and engage in civic education workshops for those approaching the voting age. Every Vote Counts is not affiliated with a political party, but essentially is a member organization of concerned citizens.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The objective of Every Vote Counts at its core is rooted to this two-fold mission: more people should vote and the active voting population should reflect our nation’s demographics. To this end, our organizational divisions and offerings are tripartite. In our legislative policy and advocacy division, we oppose advances of gerrymandering and support pro-voter legislation that enhances fair districting. Next, through voter registration, social campaigns, and distribution of best practices, we hope to leverage technology along with comprehensive analysis of the practices of high turn-out nations in order to bolster robust voter engagement. Finally, we advocate at the local level in our Civic Education division through outreach to local high schools in our community and engage in civic education workshops for those approaching the voting age. Every Vote Counts is not affiliated with a political party, but essentially is a member organization of concerned citizens.

      • Guild of Carillonneurs

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Instruments

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The purpose of the Guild shall be to maintain a regular ringing schedule of the Yale Memorial Carillon in Harkness Tower during the academic year; to further the musical education of its members by, among other things, meeting regularly as a group to perform for each other and visiting other carillons at least once a year; to teach and train underclassmen in the art of carillon-playing during the annual Heel and to elect new members into the Guild after auditions at the end of Heel; to organize a carillon concert series each summer; to perform at official functions of the University; to maintain and further good relations with carillonneurs at other carillons around the world, the Guild of Carillonneurs in North America (GCNA), and the national carillon schools in Europe; to maintain and enlarge the library of music sheets and books and literature on campanology; and, to encourage general interest in the bells and the art of carillon-playing at the University and in New Haven.

      • HAPPY (Hypertension Awareness and Prevention Program at Yale)

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Health/Wellness, Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Patricia Xu, Annie Yang, Email group officers

        Mission
        HAPPY is a Yale University student organization committed to providing regular hypertension screening services, linking hypertensive patients with available care, and eliminating barriers to follow-up care for chronic hypertension, for the low-income and homeless populations around New Haven, CT. We engage student volunteers and leaders in active volunteerism, educational outreach, research, publications, fundraising, and other innovative projects to achieve highest quality of our services and maximize our service impact. We envision creating a successful model at Yale and New Haven and replication our model of success in other universities across the country by establishing a national non-profit organization.

      • Harbor Scholars: A Dwight Hall Program at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Harbor Scholars: A Dwight Hall Program at Yale is a service, scholarship, and advocacy organization that seeks to address the unique challenges faced by those who do not benefit from the personal and financial support that many of their peers receive from family, both on campus and throughout Connecticut. This identity includes but is not limited to foster youth, emancipated minors, unaccompanied minors, estranged LGBTQ+ youth, and those who lack parental support for other reasons. In order to ensure the continued success of these individuals at the collegiate level, the program provides financial assistance, winter housing accommodations, community and social support to college students of this identity, starting with Yale in its pilot phase. The program also engages in mentorship and college counseling services for youth in out-of-home care across Connecticut and youth advocacy on the state and local levels.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Harbor Scholars: A Dwight Hall Program at Yale is a service, scholarship, and advocacy organization that seeks to address the unique challenges faced by those who do not benefit from the personal and financial support that many of their peers receive from family, both on campus and throughout Connecticut. This identity includes but is not limited to foster youth, emancipated minors, unaccompanied minors, estranged LGBTQ+ youth, and those who lack parental support for other reasons. In order to ensure the continued success of these individuals at the collegiate level, the program provides financial assistance, winter housing accommodations, community and social support to college students of this identity, starting with Yale in its pilot phase. The program also engages in mentorship and college counseling services for youth in out-of-home care across Connecticut and youth advocacy on the state and local levels.

        Mission
        The purpose of Heritage Theater Ensemble shall be to foster the development of Black theater in the Yale-New Haven community: to provide a forum for the expression of Black (and other minority) talent in all aspects of the performing arts and to generate and promote a collective, artistic consciousness within the organization. Similarly, Heritage Theater Ensemble's promotion of artistic endeavors within New Haven shall be a means of developing and sustaining Black (minority) arts as a means of politicizing art-production within the local community.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission

        Mission

We are a community group for those born and bred in Hong Kong, third culture kids who lived in Hong Kong at a certain point in their lives, individuals whose families emigrated from Hong Kong, and everyone in between.       • Immigrant History Project

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic, Cultural, Media/Technology, Publication, Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Herman Peng, Shirshak Gautam, Sunnie Liu

        Mission
        At the Immigrant History Initiative, we believe in the power of storytelling to empower and drive change. Our mission is to fundamentally change to how we learn, talk, and think about race, migration, and social justice as a global society. We do this by providing comprehensive education resources that center on the histories and lived experiences of immigrant communities and people of color.

        IHI’s model has four key components: 1) multimedia curriculum & course design, 2) anti-racist resource development, 3) community engagement and empowerment, and 4) equitable education support.
        ​
        We work with students, educators, schools, communities, and organizations to share the untold stories of immigrant diasporas. Immigrant history IS American history.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Herman Peng, Shirshak Gautam, Sunnie Liu

        Mission
        At the Immigrant History Initiative, we believe in the power of storytelling to empower and drive change. Our mission is to fundamentally change to how we learn, talk, and think about race, migration, and social justice as a global society. We do this by providing comprehensive education resources that center on the histories and lived experiences of immigrant communities and people of color.

        IHI’s model has four key components: 1) multimedia curriculum & course design, 2) anti-racist resource development, 3) community engagement and empowerment, and 4) equitable education support.
        ​
        We work with students, educators, schools, communities, and organizations to share the untold stories of immigrant diasporas. Immigrant history IS American history.

      • Journal of Literary Translation

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Publication

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Journal of Literary Translation (JoLT) publishes English translations of poetry and prose, as well as essays on the theory and practice of translation. A bi-annual magazine, JoLT seeks to showcase the excellent work of translators at Yale, to think critically about translation in a variety of contexts, and to explore metaphors for translation through the physical design of each issue. We also host readings and workshops to promote literary translation in the greater community at Yale.

        Website Mission

        Group Not Registered Yet

        Mission
        Our purpose is to engage the Yale community in issues regarding Filipino culture. We achieve this goal by hosting events that raise awareness of Filipino identity, such as cooking events, weekly dinners, mixers, cultural shows, and political discussions.



        Kasama is a small club and our name - translated from Tagalog as "together" - embodies our mission to bring together members of the community both Filipino and non-Filipino. Thus Kasama is involved in the Asian American Cultural Center at Yale, The Asian American Students Alliance, and other umbrella organizations in order to embrace both Filipino and pan-Asian identity. We work closely with other groups at Yale to foster a sense of collaboration and inclusivity.

      • Korean American Students at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, AACC Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Korean American Students at Yale (KASY) was established in 1984 by a group of students who wanted to promote the cultural, political, and social interests of the community of Korean Americans at Yale. In the thirty-plus years since its inception, KASY has grown both in size and influence, but still remains dedicated to its founding principles. Known as a vibrant and thriving undergraduate organization, KASY functions as a promoter of cultural awareness, a vehicle for political action, and most importantly, a tightly-knit family.

      • La Unidad Latina, Lambda Upsilon Lambda Fraternity, Inc.

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Greek-Letter Organizations

        Website Mission

        Contact: Dennis Portillo, Email group officers

        Mission
        La Unidad Latina, Lambda Upsilon Lambda Fraternity, Incorporated primarily seeks to take a leadership role in meeting the needs of the Latino community through academic achievement, cultural awareness, community service and promotion of the Latino culture and people.

        We strive to become the premier Latino Fraternity in the country. More specifically, we strive to become a nationally recognized Latino fraternal organization comprised of the best and brightest leaders committed to excellence in service and education.

        Since its inception in 1982, La Unidad Latina has remained on the vanguard of political and community empowerment by developing influential leaders that strive to exert knowledge and power into its peers in order to attain mutual success. We commit ourselves to academic excellence, leadership development and cultural enlightenment, enhanced by a diverse cognizant membership. La Hermandad strives to preserve and promote an inclusive intellectual environment for its members, in addition to the general community.

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Maison de Beauté at Yale: An Undergraduate Organization hopes to be the dedicated group for the study and exploration of cosmetics. We hope to be the primary interface between Yale students and the world of cosmetics. We hope to examine the role of cosmetics in the anthropological, socioeconomic, cultural, and scientific spheres. We will look not only at contemporary uses of cosmetics but also investigate the history of cosmetics, going all the way back to Cleopatra and her use of perfumed oils or Catherine de Medici and her perfumes at the Santa Maria Novella apothecaries. We will attempt to answer the questions: What is beauty? And how does it interact with art and culture? This issue is especially pertinent in our world today with social justice. We will examine the use of cosmetics and “beauty” as something that defines and limits femininity and simultaneously something that empowers gender fluidity.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

      • Miracle League Dance at Yale - an Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Mission
        This organization’s mission is two-fold. This organization is intended to provide members of the surrounding New Haven community with an otherwise non existent opportunity, due to a physical, intellectual, or developmental disability, to express themselves through dance. The environment provided is intended to be relaxing and fun. The dancers attending the rehearsals will have the option of dancing without the constraints of a specific style of dance. Additionally, this organization intends to provide members of the Yale community with an opportunity to be exposed to people who overcome their respective disabilities.

      • National Society of Black Engineers

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Pre-Professional

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The National Society of Black Engineers, as a national student and professional based organization, does hereby dedicate itself to the development of intensive programs for increasing African-American and other ethnic minority participation in the field of engineering and engineering technology. These programs will be initiated both within and outside the campus community and will serve to strengthen relations between professional industry and the African-American community. Members of the organization are encouraged to join and participate in their individual professional societies. This organization will endeavor to provide general counseling to all members. The Yale University Chapter of the National Society of Black Engineers declares its intention to fulfill the mission of the national organization on Yale’s campus and in the New Haven community.

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Arts: Other, Arts: Visual Arts, Cultural, Publication, AACC Affiliate Org, Cultural: Mixed Race

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Our project aims to create a more nuanced portrait of Asian American identity by collecting and archiving the voices of students, faculty, and staff at Yale who identify as Asian or Asian American through oral history interviews, submissions of artwork and writing, and yearly exhibits of our collective voices. Our goal is to celebrate the heterogeneity of all those who consider themselves to be Asian or Asian American and, in so doing, to encourage a broader and more inclusive view of the kinds of narratives encompassed by that label.

        New Haven REACH is a student-run organization that seeks to provide the information and support necessary for New Haven youth to access the higher education best suited to their dreams, potential, and ambitions.       • Opera Theatre of Yale College

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Singing, Performance: Theater

        Website Mission

        Contact: Lena Goldstein, Emery Kerekes, Email group officers

        Mission
        The Opera Theatre of Yale College (OTYC) is the undergraduate opera company at Yale University. Our organization is entirely student-run; every show offers our members the opportunity to learn firsthand the mechanics of performing and producing an opera. Our members are singers, instrumentalists, conductors, theatre technicians, costume and set designers, choreographers, and dancers. OTYC is an immersive extracurricular experience that prepares young artists and administrators for professional life after Yale. We are committed to bringing creative, thoughtful, and innovative opera productions to the Yale and New Haven communities.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Lena Goldstein, Emery Kerekes, Email group officers

      • Outdoor Climbing at Yale: A Student Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Sports/Outdoors

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The goal of OCAY is to foster a climbing-focused outdoor culture and community. In order to do this, OCAY aims to create a community of Yale students, faculty and staff who are already outdoor climbers, mountaineers or alpinists, and to provide safety workshops and other training opportunities for new and experienced climbers alike in a safe and controlled environment. In addition to on-campus events including workshops and social events, OCAY’s ultimate goal is to lead outdoor climbing trips where members can learn from each other. As OCAY is expressly focused on outdoor climbing, we can focus our resources on providing the highest-quality climbing workshops, events, and outdoor trips.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

In addition to on-campus events including workshops and social events, OCAY’s ultimate goal is to lead outdoor climbing trips where members can learn from each other.       • Party of the Left

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Speech/Debate

        Website Mission

        Mission
        We, the Party of the Left, are a community devoted to political discourse. As such, we seek both to develop our Members as people and leaders, and to develop a new vision of the American Left. Our means are spirited discussion and formal debate of the politics, policies, and philosophies that divide our community. We value intellectual integrity: the willingness to examine one’s innermost beliefs in a manner that is both honest and rigorous. Internally, we compete to present compelling visions of the Left. Externally, we test our ideas and abilities against our ideological opponents. We seek to bring discourse to the outside world, and the outside world to discourse. Together, we strive to advance the Party, the Yale Political Union, and the Left.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

      • Peace and Dialogue Leadership Initiative

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        1. To convey a nuanced understanding of the Israeli­Palestinian Conflict and the region as a whole by connecting high-level strategic dialogue with realities on the ground,
        2. To provide students with the tools necessary to think about the United States’ proper role in the U.S.-Israel relationship, its role in the Israeli-Palestinian relationship, and, more broadly, its role in the region,
        3. To foster civil­military understanding and dialogue,
        4. To provide an incisive look into Israeli society, culture, and politics, while simultaneously grappling with the unique security challenges facing both the U.S. and her allies in the region,
        5. To actively foster a community on college campuses interested in engaging with and discussing these issues.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

      • ReDirected Studies

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Yale ReDirected Studies commits itself to reflecting on the limitations of the ‘Western’ intellectual tradition and articulating alternatives to said tradition. With this in consideration, we strive to focus on ‘non-Western’ intellectual and cultural works typically excluded from these ‘canons,’ while consistently re-evaluating how framing as such edifies concepts like the ‘West.’ ReDirected hopes to accomplish our goals by inviting Yale’s wider community to explore traditions that developed independently from the stereotypical ‘West,’ whether wholly or in part.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

      • Refugee and Immigrant Student Education

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        RISE is a tutoring and mentoring organization that works with immigrants and refugees in New Haven to overcome language and cultural barriers they may face. Our team of tutors works through weekly in-school and in-home sessions in a variety of public schools and family homes. Our tutors work with a curriculum designed by our team, and we provide resources necessary for our ESL based programming. In addition to these weekly sessions, we organize monthly community events to allow for cultural exchanges to benefit the greater New Haven community, the immigrant and refugee populations, and the Yale community.

        Membership Benefits

      • Restaurant Rescue Project

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Restaurant Rescue Project seeks to reallocate food waste and combat local hunger through student-driven initiatives, with a focus on community integration and sustainable engagement.

        Through a network of donors and receivers, the student-run system works to combat food waste on a community level. The project partners with local restaurants, grocery stores, and supermarkets, which donate usable food that would otherwise be wasted. Student volunteers operate regular shifts and transport food from these donors to receiving facilities, including soup kitchens, halfway houses, and shelters.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

      • Rural Students Alliance at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Recognizing that students from small towns and rural communities have particular experiences that are unique from their urban peers and impact the way they experience Yale, the Rural Students Alliance of Yale is a group for rural students at Yale to get to know and support one another with the goal of improving the experience of rural students at Yale. We also aim to increase the visibility of rurality on Yale's campus, not only highlighting rural members of its student body but also increasing the presence of rurality in academic inquiry through guest speakers, panels, film screenings, and more.

      • Russian Cultural Club

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural

        Website Mission

        Contact: Aya Hall

        Mission
        The Russian Cultural Club is Yale’s official undergraduate cultural organization for Russian-speaking international students, immigrant and heritage Russian-speakers, and students of Russian and Eastern European cultures alike. In addition to organizing weekly dinners in the residential colleges, the club coordinates with the Slavic Department, the Russian Studies Project, and other undergraduate and graduate student organizations to organize cultural celebrations, screen films, invite guest speakers, and create a space on campus for the discussion and celebration of cultural traditions shared by Russian-speakers.

      • Shades A Cappella, Inc.

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Singing

        Website Mission

        Contact: Gabrielle Barnes, Dzidedi Azumah, Email group officers

        Mission
        Shades is an all gender a cappella group founded to celebrate music of the African Diaspora. It is our objective to offer a unique, musically excellent, and spiritually enriching performance experience to audiences at Yale University and beyond. Drawing from the diverse backgrounds of our members and the oral traditions of Black people across the globe, we strive to portray authentically the complexity of the Black experience. In addition to mastering the style of our music, we develop an appreciation of its history and roots in order to educate audiences about our music’s lineage. We acknowledge and accept that we are endowed with both the responsibility and the privilege of giving a voice to the voiceless, and we aim to do so through the richness of our repertoire with its power to inspire and unite us and our audiences.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Gabrielle Barnes, Dzidedi Azumah, Email group officers

        Mission
        Shades is an all gender a cappella group founded to celebrate music of the African Diaspora.       • Shaka: Yale's Undergraduate Polynesian Dance Group

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Dance

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Shaka is a Polynesian dance group that celebrates and shares traditional and modern styles of Hula and Tahitian dance with the Yale community. The popular Hawaiian gesture "shaka," meaning "hang loose," is used to convey the friendship, love, and compassion of the "Aloha Spirit" among friends and strangers alike.

        Shaka aims to celebrate the Polynesian culture and Aloha Spirit with the Yale community by performing authentic dance from the islands of Hawaii and Tahiti.

      • SheCode

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        As our society becomes more and more technologically advanced, computer science becomes increasingly important and relevant. However, programming is inaccessible to many minority groups, especially women. We believe that teaching programming skills to girls will inspire and foster an interest in computer science. Moreover, our classes expose students to a technical field and allow them to create concrete products and instill value of perseverance, creativity, ownership, and achievement. SheCode wants to lower the initial intimidation barrier of computer science and create a supportive environment where students of all background can learn, collaborate, and create something incredible.

      • Smart Woman Securities

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Pre-Professional

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Smart Woman Securities (SWS) Yale and aims to empower undergraduate women of all academic backgrounds and all career interests with investment knowledge. Founded in 2010, it is the first finance organization for women at Yale. Through instructive seminars, mentoring initiatives, and meetings with successful investors such as Warren Buffett, SWS provides resources upon which women can build greater knowledge of financial markets. By giving young women direct investment experience while still in college, SWS aims to empower a new generation of women investors for the future.

        The purpose of this student chapter is to:

      • South Asian Society

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, AACC Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The South Asian Society at Yale (SAS) is an organization of social, cultural, and intellectual exchange for those with a special interest in South Asia (Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka). The mission of SAS is threefold: to increase awareness of South Asian and South Asian American political issues, to increase South Asian cultural awareness, and to serve as a social tie for the South Asian community at Yale University. SAS is not necessarily just for South Asians: it is open to all that share an interest in any aspect of South Asia. Everyone is welcome in this organization.

        Membership Benefits

      • South Slavic Society

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The South Slavic Society at Yale is committed to the promotion of culture and history of Balkans within the university community. The organization’s main objective will be the contribution to better understanding of the geo-political situation and the cultural conglomerate of the South-Eastern Europe through history to present. Another important purpose of our organization is to provide a sense of community to the Yale students with South Slavic origins or interest in South Slavic culture. Through a series of social gatherings, speaker discussions and networking events, we will seek to cultivate the culture, historical legacy, language and traditions of our countries.

      • Steppin' Out

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Dance, AfAm Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Contact: Moises Cosme, Celia Cacho

        Mission
        Step is an African American dance form developed first by South African miners as an alternative to drumming, a previously banned activity. There is a vibrant step dance tradition in the South, but in the Northeast many people have never even heard of it. Steppin' Out aims to share this great history and culture with the Yale community, both by making the otherwise unknown style visible in the first place and by celebrating the diversity of our membership.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Moises Cosme, Celia Cacho

        Mission
        Step is an African American dance form developed first by South African miners as an alternative to drumming, a previously banned activity. There is a vibrant step dance tradition in the South, but in the Northeast many people have never even heard of it. Steppin' Out aims to share this great history and culture with the Yale community, both by making the otherwise unknown style visible in the first place and by celebrating the diversity of our membership.

With collaborative, interdisciplinary student teams, we use any skills we can offer (survey collection, data analysis, education) to assist in addressing a specific public health problem in each community that we’re working with.

      • The Black Solidarity Conference at Yale

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Black Solidarity Conference at Yale is a completely student-run annual conference held in February. BSC is the largest undergraduate conference held at Yale University and it continues to grow each year! BSC invites over 700 undergraduates of of various races, religions, ethnicities, and communities to discuss issues pertaining to the African Diaspora. Through discussions, panels, networking, and social gatherings, students from across the country analyze issues affecting the Black/Afro-Diasporic community and explore solutions that can be implemented on their own college campuses. In the past, the Conference has hosted Drs. Michael Eric Dyson, Angela Davis, Nikki Giovanni, and Cornel West as keynote speakers. We've also hosted artists such as J. Cole, Big Sean, Vic Mensa, and Phony Ppl as concert performers! In the following pages, you can discover how to register for conference and be a part of this amazing experience!

      • The Elmseed Enterprise Fund

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Entrepreneurial/Business, Pre-Professional

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Founded by enterprising Yale undergraduates in 2001, Elmseed has become a valuable resource for over 500 New Haven businesses.

        Elmseed is staffed entirely by Yale undergraduates dedicated to New Haven small business. We provide motivated entrepreneurs with access to one-on-one personalized consulting, business training, technical assistance, and a network of peer support. In doing so, Elmseed aims to empower entrepreneurs who lack the resources necessary to start or expand small businesses. Elmseed is committed to encouraging and enabling sustainable economic self-reliance in the greater New Haven area.

      • The Independent Party

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Speech/Debate

        Website Mission

        Contact: Caroline Beit

        Mission
        The Independent Party of the Yale Political Union is the premier forum for free and authentic student debate at Yale. One of the founding parties of the Yale Political Union, the IP is easily the Union’s largest party and the only one that adheres to no specific ideology or political viewpoint; instead we aim to foster robust, open, and wide-ranging political discourse.

        Our weekly debates are open to the entire Yale community and address challenging political, cultural, and philosophical issues. Our debate format is easily accessible and relies on Robert’s Rules of Order to ensure that all voices are heard and respected. We encourage everyone–the casual visitor and committed member alike–to ask tough questions, give speeches, and actively explore their own convictions. Recently, we have debated some of the following resolutions: Resolved: Kill the Death Penalty; Resolved: Hypocrisy is Not Immoral; Resolved: WikiLeaks is Good for America; Resolved: Go West, Young Man; and Resolved: Defund the Arts

        The Independent Party’s motto is “Hear All Sides,” and this is an imperative by which we live. At our debates, you will find bold expressions of opinions from across the political spectrum. One could say that the IP is home to libertarians, socialists, neo-conservatives, hard-line moderates, and almost everything in between–but in fact, we are a group of students who resist the claustrophobic categories of “liberal” and “conservative” popular in today’s politics and reject the partisan pressures that demand adherence to a mass-produced political platform, in favor of intellectually honest and authentic approaches to forming and evaluating our worldviews. In the Independent Party we believe that openness of mind is the truest mark of genuine intelligence.

        Along with our debates, the Independent Party hosts a wide variety of social events throughout the academic year. Whether watching a movie, arguing over drinks, or toasting at Mory’s, IPsters are always having fun together. As we like to say, we take our ideas seriously, but we don’t take ourselves too seriously. The IP is one of the closest groups of friends you will find at Yale; the friendships formed in the IP stay with us forever.

        We also go to New York City every semester to meet with prominent politicians, journalists, business people, artists, and media personalities. In recent semesters, we have meet with former New York Mayor Ed Koch, Obama Administration health care expert Dr. Ezekiel Emmanuel, Editor-in-Chief of The New Atlantis Eric Cohen, CEO of the New York Public Library Tony Marx, UN Ambassador John Bolton, Historian Eric Foner, and the late William F. Buckley, Jr.

        “Yale,” George Pierson famously said, “is at once a tradition, a company of scholars, a society of friends.” The Independent Party is much the same. Please join us at one of our debates this Fall and learn firsthand what this party is all about.

        Membership Benefits

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission

      • The University Curlers at Yale Undergraduate Division

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Sports/Outdoors

        Website Mission

        Mission
        This organisation has been formed to create opportunities for graduate and undergraduate students at Yale to jointly curl socially and competitively, to preserve the traditions of curling and to encourage the camaraderie and sportsmanship of the game. All graduate and undergraduate students at Yale University are invited to participate. This club will be an integration of collegiate curling within the USCA with traditional social and competitive aspects of curling which centre around the spirit of curling. The spirit of curling, specifically the canon of respect for others irrespective of their background, beliefs, gender, sexual orientation, disability or race, shall be honoured and actively pursued by all members.

      • The Yale Alley Cats - An Undergraduate A Cappella Singing Group

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Singing

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Yale Alley Cats is an undergraduate a-cappella singing group whose purpose is to sing wonderful music together, to learn to become better musicians through vocal performance and rehearsal, to spread our music to Yale University students and faculty, and to perform for music enthusiasts, both young and old, all around the world. The Yale Alley Cats, Inc. is registered as a non-profit organization, and we are therefore exempt from taxes. Officers include the Business Manager, the Pitchpipe (or Musical Director), the Rush Managers, and the Tour Managers. These officers are appointed unanimously by the members of the current group after a series of presentations and deliberations in the spring. The Alley Cats’ funds are used to cover the necessary expenses of the group, including travel, lodging, album production, publicity, and other basic operating costs. As one of Yale’s oldest and most renowned a-cappella groups (having been established in 1943), The Yale Alley Cats strive to uphold the strong tradition of a-cappella music that has become such a signature of Yale’s student life.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission

The Yale Alley Cats, Inc. is registered as a non-profit organization, and we are therefore exempt from taxes.       • The Yale Herald Inc.

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Publication

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Yale Herald, a weekly Yale undergraduate publication, is nestled in the sweet spot between magazine and newspaper. Since 1986, the Herald has aimed to provide in-depth, analytical reporting and includes personal essays, interviews and profiles, culture articles, creative writing, reviews, humor, and feature coverage of campus and local happenings. With a circulation of over 2,000, the Herald is the second-highest circulated campus publication and is distributed free of charge throughout the Yale campus and New Haven businesses. Rachel Calcott, BC '22, and Hamzah Jhaveri, TC '23, serve as Editors-in-Chief of the Herald for the 2020-2021 academic year.

      • The Yale Roosevelt Institute - An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Advocacy/Policy

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Mission
        We aim to empower students actively interested in the pressing issues around them with the resources necessary to impact change. By fostering a community of progressive activism on the Yale campus, we seek to inspire students to become leaders of their community at the local and national level.

        Membership Benefits
        - Connect with real-world experts through partner organizations.
        - Access speaker events with leaders in your area of interest, such as Neera Tanden, former director of domestic policy for the Obama-Biden presidential campaign.
        - Learn important research skills through our workshops, which provide training in data analysis tools, policy writing, and more.
        - Gain hands-on research experience and learn how to structure and approach problems combining qualitative and quantitative aspects of a central question.
        - Access a national network of students and policy leaders through the Roosevelt National branch, which extends across 38 states and 120 campuses.
        - Mentorship and opportunities to meet with, work with, and learn from Roosevelt leadership, who have experience in policy research.
        - Gain the opportunity to contribute to and be featured in your policy center’s final report and Op-Ed.
