      • The Yale Women's Center - An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Advocacy/Policy, Cultural, Leadership, Political, Social

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Women’s Center works across issues and identities toward collective liberation. Gender and sexuality have historically been central to our work and now serve as one of many points of entry into intersectional struggles and coalition building.

        We seek to foster a self-critical and self-reflective community, intentionally directing our time, resources, and programming toward dismantling systems of oppression through education and action. We aim to provide a physical and intellectual space where all are able to collaborate, learn, and unlearn without judgment. We strive to make our work accessible to everyone who wishes to engage with it, firmly believing that this work cannot and should not be done in isolation.

        The Women’s Center may be spatially enclosed within and funded by Yale, but all work within the university is intertwined with New Haven. We strive to build a deep and long-standing relationship with the city: realizing our mission demands that our community and our efforts extend far beyond our campus.

        Membership Benefits

      • Trans@Yale: An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Advocacy/Policy, LGBTQ

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The three goals of Trans@Yale are: to provide a safe space for transgender and/or non-binary students to form a community that provides emotional support and any needed medical advice; to work with the Yale administration to provide respect and support, individually and institutionally, for trans and non-binary students; and to engage with larger-scale sociopolitical advocacy and activism around issues affecting the trans community as well as other communities fighting for rights and recognition. The first goal will be achieved through hosting social events and meetings where students can be themselves and feel comfortable and safe, as well as hosting workshops and talks on key trans issues. The second goal will be achieved through student activism, and also by working with the Office of LGBTQ Resources and the Yale Administration to find and rewrite policies that currently exclude trans/non-binary students and/or make being trans and participating in a Yale-affiliated activity unusually difficult. The third goal will be achieved also through student activism, as well as collaboration with other on-campus organizations and New Haven groups.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The three goals of Trans@Yale are: to provide a safe space for transgender and/or non-binary students to form a community that provides emotional support and any needed medical advice; to work with the Yale administration to provide respect and support, individually and institutionally, for trans and non-binary students; and to engage with larger-scale sociopolitical advocacy and activism around issues affecting the trans community as well as other communities fighting for rights and recognition. The first goal will be achieved through hosting social events and meetings where students can be themselves and feel comfortable and safe, as well as hosting workshops and talks on key trans issues. The second goal will be achieved through student activism, and also by working with the Office of LGBTQ Resources and the Yale Administration to find and rewrite policies that currently exclude trans/non-binary students and/or make being trans and participating in a Yale-affiliated activity unusually difficult. The third goal will be achieved also through student activism, as well as collaboration with other on-campus organizations and New Haven groups.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Whim 'n Rhythm

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Singing

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        As of 1981, Yale’s vibrant a cappella scene featured a dozen underclassman groups of every variety. However, seven senior women felt that a key part of their musical experience was missing – a senior group. These seven seniors founded Whim n’ Rhythm as an answer to the decades-old tradition of The Whiffenpoofs. Thirty-six years later, the 13 singers of Whim n’ Rhythm represent the best and most experienced female musicians of the senior class.

        Each year, Whim has continued to grow into a full-force presence on Yale’s campus and on both the national and international stages. The group tours domestically and in the greater New England area yearly, visiting locations from New York and Los Angeles to Hong Kong and Cairo, and recently founded a full-fledged Alumnae Board to help build the group’s legacy from beyond Yale’s campus. Post-commencement, the group traditionally takes a five-to-seven week World Tour, hitting nearly every continent.

        Prospective singers audition in the spring of their junior year to be tapped into Whim for their senior year the following fall. Whim represents nearly every underclassman singing group, a variety of residential colleges and academic majors, and hometowns ranging from coast to coast.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        As of 1981, Yale’s vibrant a cappella scene featured a dozen underclassman groups of every variety. However, seven senior women felt that a key part of their musical experience was missing – a senior group. These seven seniors founded Whim n’ Rhythm as an answer to the decades-old tradition of The Whiffenpoofs. Thirty-six years later, the 13 singers of Whim n’ Rhythm represent the best and most experienced female musicians of the senior class.

        Each year, Whim has continued to grow into a full-force presence on Yale’s campus and on both the national and international stages. The group tours domestically and in the greater New England area yearly, visiting locations from New York and Los Angeles to Hong Kong and Cairo, and recently founded a full-fledged Alumnae Board to help build the group’s legacy from beyond Yale’s campus.       • William F. Buckley, Jr. Program

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Political

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The mission of the William F. Buckley, Jr. Program is to promote intellectual diversity at Yale University. We aim to expand political discourse on campus and to expose students to often-unvoiced views. We believe that ideas have consequences and that genuine intellectual diversity is essential for advancing critical inquiry and avoiding ideological complacency. Our hope is that by providing a home for a diverse collection of serious conservative thought we can provide a forum for Yale students to consider and examine a range of political philosophies to which they are rarely exposed. As such, the purpose of this program is to foster open political discussion and intellectual engagement on campus.

      • Y-BioIncubator: A Student Collaborative

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Medical/Nursing/Public Health

        Website Mission

        Mission
        YBI hopes to unite the Yale-connected undergraduate, graduate, and professional engineering communities by providing a space for those interested in pursuing biological innovation in the health and medical fields. We want to give biological innovation a prominent stake on this campus. We will provide professional development workshops for these students, weekly lectures to expand their knowledge of current bio-innovations, plan trips to local biotech/medtech companies, and collaborate with CBIT/Tsai CITY to bring more medical technology creation resources to undergraduates. Lastly, we will provide students the opportunity to be involved in year-long medical device/global health technology projects, focused on mechanical devices, that will be vetted with CEID staff and CBIT.

      • Yale College Anime Society

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, Social

        Website Mission

        Contact: Slater Smith, Eleanor Iskander

        Mission
        The purpose of the Yale College Anime Society is to allow people to appreciate East Asian culture--especially Japanese culture--through the lens of media and entertainment. We hope to give people the opportunity to explore genres and mediums they may have never explored. We primarily hope to do this through exposure to, discussion of, and analysis of Japanese Animation and Comics (i.e. "anime" and "manga"), Japanese music, and Japanese culture in general but will also look at manhwas, webtoons, light novels, and a variety of other mediums and genres . Through this, we aim to broaden the overall appeal and awareness of Eastern Asian media and entertainment, such as anime and manga, and increase the presence of this unique art form in the mainstream consciousness.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Slater Smith, Eleanor Iskander

      • Yale College Bridge Club

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Games/Gaming

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Bridge: It’s not your grandmother’s card game.
        Well, actually, it may very well be your grandmother’s card game. Still, bridge is a fun and challenging game for all ages with depth rivaling that of chess, go, and other popular pastimes. In addition, as a partnership game, bridge is also social—a fun activity for friends and a great way to meet new people. Bridge can be learned by middle schoolers, but remains challenging for 40 year veterans of the game.
        The Yale College Bridge Club exists to introduce new players to the game and support the game on campus and in the community. Our weekly games are informal and open to beginners and experts alike. If you’re fond of puzzles, math, or other games, have family or friends who play, or are just looking for an interesting hobby, come check us out!

        Membership Benefits

      • Yale College Council

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Student Government

        Website Mission

        Contact: Aliesa Bahri, Reilly Johnson, Email group officers

        Mission
        The purpose of YCC shall be to pursue the improvement of the Yale undergraduate experience by lending a voice to student concerns and opinions, shaping University policy, protecting student rights and freedoms, promoting and financing undergraduate organizations, fostering school unity and pride, and serving as a forum for the discussion and advancement of student ideas. We shall serve as the primary liaison between the undergraduate student body and the administration, graduate schools, faculty, staff, alumni, and persons or groups outside of the University. Any issue affecting the quality of undergraduate life or education falls within the jurisdiction of YCC.

      • Yale Dominican Student Association

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        DSA was founded with the intent of spreading awareness concerning the Dominican experience and culture. These goals shall be met through:

        (a) Sponsoring informative and social events that will aid in addressing issues concerning Dominicans and other Latinos. These events shall be open to the entire Yale and New Haven community.

        (b) Concentrating its efforts on recruitment and retention of Dominican students by developing academic and personal support networks for undergraduate students, and establishing networks with professionals and DSA alumni.

        (c) Striving to serve Dominican communities in the United States and abroad through community service.

        (d) Obtaining historical and updated information about the Dominican Republic, in order to serve as a resource to the Yale community on Dominican affairs.

        Membership Benefits

      • Yale Ecology and Evolutionary Biology Undergraduate Group

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic, Science/Technology

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Yale Ecology and Evolutionary Biology Undergraduate Group (YEEBUG) is a student organization committed to furthering educational, social, and community service opportunities for undergraduates interested in ecology and evolutionary biology. Open to all Yale undergraduates, YEEBUG will function to increase interaction among students outside the classroom and to encourage meaningful connections with faculty members in the natural sciences. Through field trips, study group meetings, forums, workshops, guest lectures, and special student-faculty dinners, YEEBUG will foster a community and make widely available the resources of Yale's Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology. YEEBUG also will actively promote student involvement in biology-related activities that serve the local community. YEEBUG will encourage members to volunteer together at educational events held at the Peabody Museum of Natural History in New Haven.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Yale Ecology and Evolutionary Biology Undergraduate Group (YEEBUG) is a student organization committed to furthering educational, social, and community service opportunities for undergraduates interested in ecology and evolutionary biology. Open to all Yale undergraduates, YEEBUG will function to increase interaction among students outside the classroom and to encourage meaningful connections with faculty members in the natural sciences. Through field trips, study group meetings, forums, workshops, guest lectures, and special student-faculty dinners, YEEBUG will foster a community and make widely available the resources of Yale's Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology. YEEBUG also will actively promote student involvement in biology-related activities that serve the local community. YEEBUG will encourage members to volunteer together at educational events held at the Peabody Museum of Natural History in New Haven.

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Publication

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Yale Economic Review is a platform for discussion, opinion, and excellent undergraduate writing on economic topics.

        As such, the YER is dedicated to sharing insights from Yale students and other community members on recent and important developments in economics to a sophisticated yet broad audience. The YER seeks to unite students and faculty in furthering the goals of Yale University, and in strengthening Yale’s reputation as one of the world's leading academic institutions in the fields of economics, policy, and finance.

        Finally, the YER is committed to providing members with a diverse community of fellow economics, policy and finance enthusiasts, with exposure to the top economic minds in business and politics through speaker series and workshops, and with a variety of career, writing, and other support resources.

        Priority publication, regular updates from the YER, access to interviews/ workshops with industry leaders, alumni at top firms and professors

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        We are a coalition dedicated to advocacy and community-building for all First-gen and/or low-income students at Yale.         - opportunities to take on projects that make real, impactful changes

      • Yale International Relations Association - An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Advocacy/Policy, International Affairs, Leadership, Political, Pre-Professional, Professional, Publication, Service/Volunteering, Speech/Debate

        Website Mission

        Contact: David Yu, Email group officers

        Mission
        After the political turbulence of the 1960s, a group of Yale students came together seeking to promote a better understanding of global affairs. As a result, in 1969, the Yale International Relations Association (YIRA) was founded.
        The Yale International Relations Association strives to foster conversation about international relations on campus and beyond through conferences, classes, travel, publications, and speaker and social events. We aim to create an inclusive, diverse, and accessible educational space for students, providing resources that enrich public speaking, leadership, critical analysis, and problem-solving abilities so members may best apply their passion for international relations and give back to the world.

        Membership Benefits

      • Yale Journal of Medicine and Law: An Undergraduate Publication

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Publication

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Yale Journal of Medicine and Law: An Undergraduate Publication is Yale’s premier publication focusing on the ever-growing crossroads between law and medicine. Since its inception in 2003, the Journal has been at the forefront of issues like healthcare policy, bioethics, healthcare economics, biomedical research, and global health care. We have featured interviews with prominent figures including US Senators, directors of organizations such as the CDC and NIH, and the US Surgeon General. Our Executive Board is comprised of students from a variety of backgrounds with foci in both medicine and law, and our Advisory Board includes prominent academicians and leaders from Yale University and beyond. Our aim is to provide our wide readership with a view of the most pressing issues and exciting advances at the intersection of medicine and law.

        Membership Benefits

      • Yale Medical Professions Outreach - An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Medical/Nursing/Public Health

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        YMPO is an undergraduate program dedicated to broadening the horizons of Yale students interested in medicine. Members have opportunities to learn about medicine directly from professionals by shadowing physician-mentors in their work environments. Students can also learn about health-related issues through various lectures, panel discussions, and events held throughout the year. Event topics include medically-related volunteer opportunities, conversations with admissions officers from various medical schools and physicians from a wide range of specialties, and local and international outreach work. Additionally, we understand the importance of teamwork and mentorship in fostering a community of future doctors and leaders in medicine by holding an annual mentoring program that connects Yale undergraduate students with Yale medical students.

        Membership Benefits

      • Yale Model Congress (Undergraduate)

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Political, Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Since 1993, Yale Model Congress has devoted itself to staging conferences that provide our high school delegates with the opportunity to assume the responsibilities of our elected representatives and to tackle the issues that face our nation. We strive to provide delegates with an engaging, fulfilling, and intimate environment in which to fight for their legislation, debate their opinions, and deepen their understanding of how our government works. By the end of four days together, we hope that all delegates leave with a greater appreciation for the nature of American democracy and with the inspiration to be active citizens in the future.

        Membership Benefits

      • Yale NROTC Undergraduate Association

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Funding, Pre-Professional, Service/Volunteering, Social

        Website Mission

        Contact: Caroline Thomason, Valente Hernandez-Bautista, Email group officers

        Mission
        We are committed to ensuring that all members have every opportunity to develop as young officers (for those who are NROTC midshipmen), and as Yale students, mentally, morally, and physically. Often, the cost of required NROTC events and training evolutions cannot be covered by official NROTC unit funds, meaning that the cost is passed down to the midshipmen. We want to ensure that no midshipmen is ever limited in their training as future officers, and therefore strive to provide them with the resources they need. As an organization, the three main resources we provide are (1) an inclusive community for all members, (2) financial assistance for ROTC training activities, and (3) events that connect Association members with the U.S. Navy, Yale NROTC alumni, and the many resources provided by Yale University.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Caroline Thomason, Valente Hernandez-Bautista, Email group officers

        Mission

      • Yale Panhellenic Council - An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Greek-Letter Organizations

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Yale Panhellenic Council is a representative government body that oversees the four sororities at Yale and coordinates formal Sorority Recruitment. We meet regularly to discuss Greek life at Yale, as well as plan recruitment. Our job is to make recruitment as fun and simple as possible. We are at your disposal to answer any questions you might have in a non-biased, impartial way, and to help you through the recruitment process. We also hold events outside of recruitment period, including during Bulldog Days. ​We operate in accordance with the National Panhellenic Council rules and regulations. For information, please visit https://www.npcwomen.org/.

      • Yale Progressive Christian Student Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Religious/Spiritual

        Website Mission

        Mission
        We hope to be authentic, connected, and engaged in and with the Yale and New Haven community.
        Authentic: We strive to remind the community that self-worth is something not tied to grades or accomplishments. We value human diversity, affirming all of our members and standing against discrimination where it is found.
        Connected: We work to make connections across Yale’s schools and are open to Yale undergraduate, graduate, and professional students. We hope to create an inclusive and interdenominational Christian community that accepts differences in members’ denominations, theologies, and practices.
        Engaged: We seek to follow the life and teachings of Jesus Christ and work to promote love, justice, and compassion on our campus and beyond.

        Mission
        Yale Queer + Asian is an organization dedicated to creating a space for people of Asian heritage who identify within the LGBTQ+ spectrum. We hold discussions examining the intersections of Asian and queer identity, invite guest speakers to present on their work and experiences and also aim to create a supportive, safe community where students are able to explore their identity and conflicts, and find fellow students who have had similar experiences. Collectively, we can build a strong community to bring attention to issues queer people of Asian heritage may face. We are associated with both the Co-Op and the AACC in their efforts on and off campus.

      • Yale Society of Physics Students

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Science/Technology

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Yale Society of Physics Students seeks to promote mentorship, fellowship, and an esprit de corps within the physics communities at Yale. We do this by hosting study sessions, information panels, prize lectures, and other academic and social events — all aimed at connecting physics students, faculty, and the Department at large. We also support education, research, and outreach endeavors in physics, hosting a number of resources and student-oriented guides for members of SPS. We communicate with the Physics DUS and the Physics Department Chair’s office to ensure undergraduate input and involvement in administrative decisions. Yale SPS has been a registered chapter of the national Society of Physics Students, and an American Institute of Physics (AIP) member organization since 1998, as well as (soon-to-be) a chapter of the Sigma Pi Sigma honor society since 2020. Through our membership, we link Yale students with other SPS chapters and the national organization, so that they may benefit from a larger community and get access to scholarships, conferences, and other initiatives.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Yale Society of Physics Students seeks to promote mentorship, fellowship, and an esprit de corps within the physics communities at Yale. We do this by hosting study sessions, information panels, prize lectures, and other academic and social events — all aimed at connecting physics students, faculty, and the Department at large. We also support education, research, and outreach endeavors in physics, hosting a number of resources and student-oriented guides for members of SPS. We communicate with the Physics DUS and the Physics Department Chair’s office to ensure undergraduate input and involvement in administrative decisions. Yale SPS has been a registered chapter of the national Society of Physics Students, and an American Institute of Physics (AIP) member organization since 1998, as well as (soon-to-be) a chapter of the Sigma Pi Sigma honor society since 2020. Through our membership, we link Yale students with other SPS chapters and the national organization, so that they may benefit from a larger community and get access to scholarships, conferences, and other initiatives.

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Advocacy/Policy

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Sena Sugiono, Email group officers

        Mission
        Increase public awareness about sustainable energy, its challenges, and its opportunities. Connect Yale students, lead energy ventures and enhance their potential. Accelerate student-led-initiatives and make Yale a leading player in energy initiatives of colleges and universities. Capitalize on interdisciplinary majors, concentrations, and interests of students, to envision and promote viable solutions to pressing energetic and environmental problems.

        Membership Benefits
        You will gain information and knowledge about energy from a multidisciplinary perspective, taking into account considerations from the following subject areas: economic/entrepreneurship, political/policy-making, scientific/engineering.

        You will be able to acquire transferable skills such as policy making, prototyping and design, effective idea presentation, and an entrepreneurial venture spirit. You can then apply them to your future career, regardless of your industry or line of work.

        Feel free to join! If you have any problems, feel free to email sena.sugiono@yale.edu and he will help add you to the group.

      • Yale Students of Mixed Heritage - an undergraduate organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, AACC Affiliate Org, AfAm Affiliate Org, NACC Affiliate Org, La Casa Affiliate Org, Cultural: Mixed Race

        Website Mission

        Contact: Jacqueline Hayre-Pérez

        Mission
        Yale Students of Mixed Heritage is intended to be a space wherein students of more than one heritage, however they choose to self-identify (whether that be racial, ethnic, cultural, national, etc) feel welcome and included in the fullness of their identity. To that end, we are committed to being a bridge between the various cultural houses and student organizations of which our members belong while also creating a space to celebrate the identity unique to being blended or mixed. We also collaborate with similar student organizations across the country, including groups at Brown, Columbia, Harvard, UCLA, UC Berkeley, UT Austin, Middleburry, and several others.

      • Yale Summer Science Research Institute - an Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Service/Volunteering

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Yale Summer Science Research Institute (SSRI) connects qualified high school students from the New Haven area with scientific research labs at Yale. We hope to provide high-quality research experiences to New Haven students in order to excite them about scientific investigation, enable them to explore new scientific fields, and increase their college preparedness. In doing so, we hope to foster long-term relationships between Yale laboratories and qualified high school students who are enthusiastic about furthering the laboratories’ research.

        The program also provides a framework for a mutually beneficial summer experience for both the students and labs. Yale undergraduate students supplement lab work for the high school interns with organized workshops and other mentorship activities. We also work to cultivate a sense of community among the students, organizing events to facilitate social interactions among the interns, as well as between the interns and their undergraduate, graduate, and professor mentors.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission

      • Yale Undergraduate Association for African Peace and Development

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - International Affairs

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Yale Undergraduate Association for African Peace and Development (YAAPD) seeks to ignite passion among students and youth at-large for conflict resolution, peace, and development on the continent. Cognizant of awareness, discourse, and action as a driver of continental development, the YAAPD hopes to prepare students’ and youth interested in Africa for efficacious and consequential careers focusing on Africa.

        As a a resident group of the Afro-American Cultural Center at Yale, YAAPD aims to complement Yale’s liberal arts curriculum with a holistic approach to learning about development, peace, and conflict resolution. Acting from our core values of education, awareness, and service, YAAPD will bring together a community of scholars, professionals and activists who are integral in the pursuit of systematic advancement and development. YAAPD seeks to:

        Develop networks among students and professionals across a spectrum of fields and interests with the aim of promoting peace and development within Africa.

        Create awareness about issues facing Africa and provide a platform to discuss strategic ways that students on the continent and abroad can resolve these issues.

        Encourage and develop, conflict resolution and development initiatives of students interested in Africa

      • Yale Undergraduate Chamber Orchestra

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Instruments

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Our purpose is to bring often-ignored chamber orchestra masterpieces into the limelight at Yale. Works like Strauss’s Metamorphosen, Bartok’s Music for Strings, Percussion, and Celesta, and the Lark Ascending are often excluded from the repertoire of current Yale ensembles. This is due to both instrumentation restrictions in the case of YSO, and ability restrictions in the case of the two college orchestras, as these pieces require a high technical and musical level.
        We also seek to introduce new works for chamber orchestra into the repertoire. YUCO provides a space for up-and-coming composers to premiere their works in a welcoming, pre-professional environment, where they can be recorded and submitted to competitions and music schools.
        YUCO is, first and foremost, a performance ensemble. YUCO can also be a meaningful stepping stone for composers, conductors, and instrumentalists on their way to graduate school and on their career paths. YUCO introduces repertoire to musicians and audience members alike that would have never played or heard otherwise.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Our purpose is to bring often-ignored chamber orchestra masterpieces into the limelight at Yale. Works like Strauss’s Metamorphosen, Bartok’s Music for Strings, Percussion, and Celesta, and the Lark Ascending are often excluded from the repertoire of current Yale ensembles. This is due to both instrumentation restrictions in the case of YSO, and ability restrictions in the case of the two college orchestras, as these pieces require a high technical and musical level.
        We also seek to introduce new works for chamber orchestra into the repertoire. YUCO provides a space for up-and-coming composers to premiere their works in a welcoming, pre-professional environment, where they can be recorded and submitted to competitions and music schools.
        YUCO is, first and foremost, a performance ensemble. YUCO can also be a meaningful stepping stone for composers, conductors, and instrumentalists on their way to graduate school and on their career paths. YUCO introduces repertoire to musicians and audience members alike that would have never played or heard otherwise.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

YUCIH aims to provide preventive care for clinics through free diagnostic tests for chronic illnesses.

      • Yale Undergraduate Kalaa

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Cultural, Performance: Dance, AACC Affiliate Org

        Website Mission

        Mission
        We are Yale's newest Indian Classical Dance group. As of now, our group includes Bharatanatyam, Kathak and Kuchipudi dancers.

        'The Yale Kalaa' is a hub through which trained classical undergraduate and graduate dancers can get the opportunity to start performing for various events on campus. The team usually has weekly two hour practices and each dance form usually practices another 3-4 hours/month. If you have any experience in classical dance, we would love to hear from you!

        In case you were wondering, 'Kalaa' (pronounced "cuh-laa") is a Sanskrit word meaning "a skilled craft" and we take our craft seriously. We use our craft to celebrate and share the joy of classical dance.

      • Yale Undergraduate Piano Collective

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Instruments

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        One of the hallmarks of Yale College is its renowned musical community. Outstanding instrumental musicians on campus frequently perform together in such well-regarded ensembles as the Yale Symphony Orchestra and the Yale Concert Band. Pianists, however, are required only in small numbers for these groups and may therefore find themselves somewhat isolated in their musical pursuit. Therefore, the Yale Undergraduate Piano Collective exists to promote greater musical and social cohesion among the undergraduate pianists at Yale. In particular, the YUPC organizes "studio classes," wherein pianists to play for each other to receive feedback and encounter fresh perspectives, and public performances, with an emphasis on collaborative repertoire for four, six, and eight hands.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        One of the hallmarks of Yale College is its renowned musical community. Outstanding instrumental musicians on campus frequently perform together in such well-regarded ensembles as the Yale Symphony Orchestra and the Yale Concert Band. Pianists, however, are required only in small numbers for these groups and may therefore find themselves somewhat isolated in their musical pursuit. Therefore, the Yale Undergraduate Piano Collective exists to promote greater musical and social cohesion among the undergraduate pianists at Yale.         Yale Undergraduates at Connecticut Hospice (YUCH) is an organization that provides the unique opportunity to work at a palliative care facility a short drive away from campus in Branford, CT. Volunteers provide a service that is crucial to the Hospice organization and uplifting to the patients. There are a variety of volunteer departments ranging from patient assistance to art therapy, which all immerse volunteers in the real patient care experience.

      • Yale Undergraduates for UNICEF

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - International Affairs

        Website Mission

        Contact: Chen Lin, Email group officers

        Mission
        ​Yale UNICEF is a member group of the United Nations International Children’s Fund Campus Initiative that aims to raise awareness about children’s issues—including poverty, development, safety, rights, health, education, and inclusion in their communities. Additionally, Yale UNICEF strives to contribute to efforts made on behalf of children both locally and internationally. Yale UNICEF hopes to inspire and empower members of the Yale community by providing them with both opportunities and tools to engage in student leadership, activism, and community service work on behalf of children worldwide.

      • Yale Undergraduates of Phi Beta Kappa

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic

        Website Mission

        Mission
        YPBK exists to strengthen the undergraduate community of PBK inductees at Yale University. As a constituent organization of the national Phi Beta Kappa Society, YPBK reflects the goals and values of the broader PBK community. PBK was founded in 1776 in order to promote and celebrate excellence in the liberal arts and sciences. The Yale chapter of PBK, Alpha of Connecticut, was founded in 1780. A society of scholars and ideas, the Yale chapter holds as its central mission the pursuit of “lux et veritas” (light and truth). YPBK not only seeks to encourage intellectual engagement but also to foster social bonds between students, based on a shared passion for learning and knowledge.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission

A society of scholars and ideas, the Yale chapter holds as its central mission the pursuit of “lux et veritas” (light and truth). YPBK not only seeks to encourage intellectual engagement but also to foster social bonds between students, based on a shared passion for learning and knowledge.

      • Yaledancers - An Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Performance: Dance

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Yaledancers is Yale's oldest premiere dance company. Since 1973, YD has provided Yale student dancers with access to high caliber training and performance opportunities. YD meets twice weekly for classes, taught by both industry professionals and fellow company members, on top of rehearsals for our two semester shows (Fall and Spring), which showcase original guest and student choreography here at Yale. The company performs a wide variety of dance styles, including classical and modern, ballet, jazz, contemporary, tap, musical theatre, and modern dance. YD also provides a social outlet and sense of community for members, creating lasting friendships among both graduate and undergraduate students.
        ​
        Yaledancers is also a founding member of the Alliance for Dance at Yale. ADAY serves as a collective forum for dance groups at Yale and provides classes, support, and the Dance Symposium to the Yale dance community.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission Contact: Email group officers

        Mission

      • You Can Too at Yale - an Undergraduate Organization

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Academic

        Website Mission

        Mission
        You Can Too is a completely free volunteer mentorship program dedicated to uplifting and inspiring minority youth. Far too often people of color find themselves without the tools they need to efficiently educate themselves, not only in the workings of academia but also in the workings of the world. You Can Too is dedicated to combating these educational disparities minority youth face. Our program pairs accomplished Black, Brown, and Latinx college students as mentors to Black, Brown, and Latinx high school and middle school youth. You Can Too mentors are dedicated to educating and inspiring their mentees through academic support, college preparation, and interactive discussions about Black history, politics, and relevant social issues.

        Membership Benefits

        Website Mission

        Mission
        You Can Too is a completely free volunteer mentorship program dedicated to uplifting and inspiring minority youth. Far too often people of color find themselves without the tools they need to efficiently educate themselves, not only in the workings of academia but also in the workings of the world. You Can Too is dedicated to combating these educational disparities minority youth face. Our program pairs accomplished Black, Brown, and Latinx college students as mentors to Black, Brown, and Latinx high school and middle school youth. You Can Too mentors are dedicated to educating and inspiring their mentees through academic support, college preparation, and interactive discussions about Black history, politics, and relevant social issues.

      • Young Democratic Socialists of America

        Yale College Undergraduate Organizations - Political

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Our mission is to educate and organize students and young people and to play a helpful and principled role in the movement for socialism. Within and throughout this struggle, we will articulate and defend the idea that true human liberation is impossible under capitalism. We seek social change which extends democracy into all aspects of life – social, political and economic. This is the struggle for socialism. Our vision of socialism is profoundly democratic, feminist, anti-racist, and anti-imperialist.
